article.description: Vickie Johnson's 14 points pushed her past 3,000 for her career and helped lead New York to a 65-54 win over Phoenix on Saturday.

related.description: New York's Vickie Johnson scored 14 points to eclipse the 3,000 mark in the Liberty's 65-54 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Saturday, becoming the seventh player in WNBA history have accomplished the feat.
related.title: Johnson is seventh WNBA player to top 3,000
related.headline: Johnson is seventh WNBA player to top 3,000

article.headline: New York improves to 10-0 vs. Merc at home
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Vickie Johnson didn't know until a few days
earlier that she was on the verge of becoming the seventh WNBA
player to score 3,000 points.

With the New York Liberty's game against the Phoenix Mercury
winding down, Johnson knew she was just one point away.

Johnson scored 14 points, topping the mark with a driving layup
with 1:49 remaining, to lead the Liberty to a 65-54 victory over
the Mercury on Saturday.

"I just went for it," Johnson said. "I didn't come in to
break the record. I just wanted to come out and help my team get a
victory today, and if I accomplished 3,000, then it's a bonus."

She knew she needed a basket after hitting a 3-pointer minutes
earlier.

"(Former teammate) Kym Hampton was on the side yelling, 'VJ you
need one more, let's go," Johnson said.

Johnson, the last remaining Liberty player from the league's
inaugural season in 1997, said she was unaware she was closing in
on the mark until the team's communications manager Larry Torres
informed her earlier in the week.

"I'm not really big on individual awards and stuff like that,
so I don't really keep up with the stats," Johnson said. "It's a
great accomplishment, especially when I sit back and look at it.
I'm not the Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes of the league. I'm not
the go-to player on the team. I guess that just says I'm very
consistent in what I do."

Ann Wauters had 19 points and 10 rebounds, and Crystal Robinson
added 10 points for New York (4-4), which improved to 10-0 at home
against Phoenix.

"Ann is a real presence inside for us, and she is a big target
when we throw it inside," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "She is
still very young. I don't think we have seen her full potential
yet."

Kamila Vodichkova scored 14 points, Diana Taurasi had 13 and
Penny Taylor 11 for Phoenix (3-7).

Johnson's milestone basket also gave the Liberty their first
double-digit lead at 61-51, and the Mercury got no closer than
seven the rest of the way. Wauters and Becky Hammon each made a
pair of free throws in the final 47 seconds to close the scoring.

The Mercury opened the second half with a 9-4 run and tied it at
35 on Plenette Pierson's layup with 16:11 remaining.

The Liberty then scored six points in a 43-second stretch,
capped by Johnson's fast-break layup with 14:31 left.

Phoenix pulled within 42-40 on Taurasi's 3-pointer with 12:04,
before a 3 by Elena Baranova and a jumper by Hammon pushed New
York's lead back up to seven.

"We were rolling, but we just didn't make the plays at the end
of the game to get it done," said Taurasi, who shot just 4-for-14
from the field.

Robinson's 3 with 9:15 remaining stretched the Liberty's lead to
51-42. Vodichkova's basket 3 minutes later brought the Mercury
within five at 53-48. Hammon's 3 with 3:33 left put New York's lead
back up nine, at 59-50.

"The difference in the game was we made shots when we had to,"
Coyle said. "We did a great job of executing our plays."

New York shot 51 percent (26-for-51) from the field, and limited
Phoenix to 36 percent (22-for-61).

The Liberty, who won their third straight at home and third in
four games overall, led 31-26 at halftime.

New York got off to a strong start, making four of its first
five shots. Phoenix was just 2-for-7 during the same stretch and
trailed 10-4 4:47 into the game.

Wauters, who scored eight of the Liberty's last 10 points of the
first half, gave New York its biggest lead of the first half at
27-18 with 2:24 remaining.
